SUBNET MASKS

ğŸ§  Mnemonic: "1 2 4 8 16 32 64 128"

Common subnet mask values (255.255.255.XXX)

| Bits | Binary   | Decimal |
| ---- | -------- | ------- |
| /25  | 10000000 | 128     |
| /26  | 11000000 | 192     |
| /27  | 11100000 | 224     |
| /28  | 11110000 | 240     |
| /29  | 11111000 | 248     |
| /30  | 11111100 | 252     |
| /31  | 11111110 | 254     |
| /32  | 11111111 | 255     |




/24 = 255.255.255.0     â†’ 256 IPs
/25 = 255.255.255.128   â†’ 128 IPs
/26 = 255.255.255.192   â†’ 64 IPs
/27 = 255.255.255.224   â†’ 32 IPs
/28 = 255.255.255.240   â†’ 16 IPs
/29 = 255.255.255.248   â†’ 8 IPs
/30 = 255.255.255.252   â†’ 4 IPs
/31 = 255.255.255.254   â†’ 2 IPs (special)


eg for a subnet mask /27 = 255.255.255.224   â†’ 32 IPs x 8 diffrerent subnets
usable hosts in the 7th subnet are 192.168.139.193 â†’ 192.168.139.222 

âš ï¸ BECAUSE:

The first address in the block (192.168.139.192) is the network address
The last address (192.168.139.223) is the broadcast address
These two cannot be assigned to hosts!


ğŸ”„ï¸LOOPBACKğŸ”„ï¸
	127.x.x.x is a special address block reserved only for loopback, not for normal networking.
	Loopback is used for:
	    Testing: Try a web server on your own machine at http://127.0.0.1:8000
	    Local services: Databases (like PostgreSQL or MySQL) often listen on 127.0.0.1
	    Debugging tools: Ping, traceroute, curl â€” for local testing
	    Isolated development: Your code can talk to itself over "network" without needing real networking
